## 1. Coding Principles (Clean & Maintainable Code)

### Constants Over Magic Numbers
- Replace hard-coded values with named constants.  
- Use descriptive constant names that explain the purpose.  
- Keep constants at the top of the file or in a dedicated constants file.  

### Meaningful Names
- Variables, functions, and classes should reveal their purpose.  
- Names should explain why something exists and how it is used.  
- Avoid abbreviations unless they are universally understood.  

### Smart Comments
- Code should be self-explanatory; use comments to explain *why*, not *what*.  
- Document APIs, complex algorithms, and non-obvious side effects.  

### Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- Each function should do exactly one thing.  
- Functions should be small and focused.  
- If a function needs a comment to explain what it does, split it into smaller ones.  

### DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself)
- Extract repeated code into reusable functions.  
- Share common logic through proper abstractions.  
- Maintain a single source of truth.  

### Clean Structure
- Keep related code together.  
- Organize files and folders in a logical hierarchy.  
- Use consistent naming conventions.  

### Encapsulation
- Hide implementation details.  
- Expose only clear and necessary interfaces.  
- Move nested conditionals into well-named functions.  

### Code Quality Maintenance
- Continuously refactor the codebase.  
- Fix technical debt early.  
- Always leave the code cleaner than you found it.  

